        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request ALMA extended configuration Band 6 continuum observations of CHa-4 (which has a half-light radius ~0.2\arcs) 
in order to search for emission from dust in this Ly-alpha emitting galaxy.  We do not expect to resolve this source, 
and the synthesized beam size of 0.9" will allow us to isolate emission from CHa-4 from the surrounding galaxies (see Figure 1).    
Observations at the high-frequency edge (LO1 ~262.5 GHz) of Band 6 provide the optimal combination of sensitivity (including receiver 
sensitivity and atmospheric water vapor transmission) and source flux for these observations.  The shaded red region of Figure 3 shows 
the expected FIR SED of CHa-4 and its 68% confidence range (where these uncertainties were derived from the uncertainty on beta, which 
was computed via Monte Carlo simulations during the SED fitting process).  Assuming that beta is near our predicted value, we need to 
reach a 1-sigma continuum point source sensitivity of 0.0124 mJy/beam to make a 5-sigma detection.  This can be achieved in 2.2 hours, 
for a total requested allocation of 4.1 hours when calibrations are included.

Co-I Freeland has extensive experience with radio interferometric observations (VLBA, (E)VLA, GMRT, ATCA) at centimeter wavelengths 
and is prepared to analyze and calibrate the data.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
