    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We request 4.1 hours of ALMA 262.5 GHz observations to detect dust emission from a z=4.4 Lyman-alpha selected galaxy (LAE). While LAEs were thought to be signposts of primordial star formation, they have recently been revealed to contain modest amounts of dust, seemingly at odds with the escape of Lyman alpha photons. If these galaxies are truly dusty, it implies that either a favorable interstellar medium geometry is screening the Lyman alpha photons from the dust, or large scale outflows are shifting the Lyman alpha photons from resonance. Until now, the presence of dust has only been inferred from the reddening effect on the rest-frame ultraviolet (UV) colors, which is also degenerate with the age and metallicity, thus the presence of dust is uncertain.  ALMA can directly detect this dust in emission, removing these uncertainties.  A positive detection will provide undeniable proof of the presence of dust, and possibly indicate that more obscured star formation is present at high redshift than previously thought. A non-detection will constrain the ratio of dust-obscured to un-obscured star formation to the very low level of &lt; 5% (1-sigma).
</prp:abstract>
